  {schemaJsons.map((schema) => (<script type="application/ld+json" set:html={JSON.stringify(schema)} />))}
</Fragment>

<ServiceHero
  eyebrow="Water Leak · Defrost Drain · Inlet Valve · LA Same-Day"
  title="Refrigerator Leaking Water Repair Los Angeles"
  subtitle={`Water inside the fresh-food compartment, puddle under the door, drip at the back of the unit, ice maker line cracked. Same-day across LA, Orange, Ventura, San Bernardino, Riverside. $89 residential diagnostic, waived with repair. ${phone}`}
  heroImageTitle="Refrigerator Leaking Water Repair"
/>

<section class="section">
  <div class="container narrow">
    <p class="section-number">Leak service</p>
    <h2>Where the puddle appears tells us what's wrong. We diagnose by location.</h2>

    <p>Water on the floor inside the fresh-food compartment (collecting at the bottom, sometimes pooling under crisper drawers) is almost always defrost drain clogged. The defrost drain carries melt water from the freezer's defrost cycle down to a pan near the compressor; when it clogs at year 5+, the water backs up and overflows into the fridge interior. About 40 to 50 percent of every "refrigerator leaking" call resolves at this drain clear, $200 to $300 service. Most repair shops misdiagnose this as a compressor or sealed-system failure and quote multi-thousand-dollar repairs; the actual fix is straightforward.</p>

    <p>Water on the floor outside the fridge in front (under the door, especially at the door dispenser corner) usually means ice maker fill tube cracked or door dispenser tray leaking. Water on the floor outside the fridge behind the unit usually means water inlet valve dripping or supply line connection loose. Sometimes water under a built-in Sub-Zero or Thermador Freedom unit is drain pan overflow because the compressor heat that's supposed to evaporate drain water isn't keeping up.</p>

    <p>One LA-specific consideration: in Santa Monica, Pacific Palisades, Malibu, and other marine-layer-corridor neighborhoods, sometimes the puddle on Monday morning is condensation from morning fog on cold metal surfaces, not a leak. We diagnose for that on every coastal-area call.</p>

    <p>Our techs service the full residential refrigerator lineup across LA County, Orange, Ventura, San Bernardino, Riverside. <strong>BHGS #A49573</strong>, <strong>EPA 608 Universal certified #1346255700410</strong>. $89 residential diagnostic waived with repair. BBB Accredited. Phones answered 24/7. Parent: <a href="/services/refrigerator-repair/">refrigerator repair</a>.</p>
  </div>
</section>

<section class="section section-gray">
  <div class="container narrow">
    <p class="section-number">Visual diagnostic</p>
    <h2 class="section-title">Where the water appears tells us what's wrong.</h2>
    <ul class="bullet-list">
      <li><strong>Inside the fresh-food compartment, pooling under crisper drawers.</strong> Defrost drain clogged. #1 cause.</li>
      <li><strong>Under the front of the door, dispenser corner specifically.</strong> Ice maker fill tube cracked, dispenser tray seal leaking, or in-door tank crack (LG and Samsung French-door specific).</li>
      <li><strong>Behind the unit on the floor.</strong> Water inlet valve slow drip, supply line connection loose, or drain pan overflow.</li>
      <li><strong>Steady drip on hot afternoons only.</strong> Drain pan overflow because compressor heat isn't evaporating drain water fast enough; common on aged units.</li>
      <li><strong>Misty puddle that dries by noon, only on humid mornings.</strong> Marine layer condensation in coastal LA, not a leak. Common in Santa Monica, Pacific Palisades, Malibu.</li>
    </ul>
  </div>
</section>

<section class="section">
  <div class="container narrow">
    <p class="section-number">Field observations</p>
    <h2 class="section-title">Top causes by frequency.</h2>
    <ol class="num-list">
      <li><strong>Defrost drain clogged (#1, 40 to 50% of leak calls).</strong> Year 5+ typical. Drain clears, $200 to $300 service. We sometimes find food debris, ice block, or biofilm; all clear with the same approach.</li>
      <li><strong>Water inlet valve slow drip.</strong> Year 6 to 10. Mineral deposits on diaphragm; intermittent drip behind the unit. $260 to $380.</li>
      <li><strong>Ice maker fill tube cracked.</strong> Temperature cycling damage at year 5+. $200 to $340 replacement.</li>
      <li><strong>Drain pan overflow (compressor heat inadequate).</strong> Aged units year 12+, drain pan capacity isn't enough or compressor heat dropped. $260 to $440 replacement pan plus condenser inspection.</li>
      <li><strong>Water filter housing crack or seal failure.</strong> Year 5 to 9. Slow drip from filter housing into cabinet. $260 to $440.</li>
      <li><strong>Door seal condensation buildup.</strong> Compromised seal allows warm air to infiltrate; condensation forms on the drum side and drips. Door seal replacement $200 to $380.</li>
      <li><strong>Marine layer condensation (Santa Monica / Palisades / Malibu).</strong> Not a leak; we diagnose and confirm to avoid unnecessary parts replacement.</li>
    </ol>
  </div>
</section>

<section class="section section-gray">
  <div class="container narrow">
    <p class="section-number">Brand-specific patterns</p>
    <h2 class="section-title">Built-in vs freestanding architecture.</h2>

    <h3 class="series-h3">Sub-Zero, Thermador Freedom, Liebherr built-in drain routing</h3>
    <p>Built-in units integrate into cabinetry rather than freestand, which means the defrost drain routes through toe-kick spaces or behind cabinet panels instead of straight to a back-of-unit drain pan. Service requires careful access to avoid scratching cabinet faces or damaging panel hardware. We have authorized service relationships and the experience to handle this without surrounding-cabinet damage. <a href="/brands/sub-zero-refrigerator-repair/">Sub-Zero</a> · <a href="/brands/thermador-refrigerator-repair/">Thermador</a> · <a href="/brands/liebherr-refrigerator-repair/">Liebherr</a>.</p>

    <h3 class="series-h3">LG and Samsung French-door in-door tank leaks</h3>
    <p>French-door units with in-door water tanks (specifically LG and Samsung) develop tank cracks at year 5 to 9 from temperature cycling. Water leaks into the door cavity, hidden until it shows up under the door bottom. By the time the leak is visible, internal door damage may have started. Replacement $440 to $680 to access and replace tank. <a href="/brands/lg-refrigerator-repair/">LG</a> · <a href="/brands/samsung-refrigerator-repair/">Samsung</a>.</p>

    <h3 class="series-h3">Whirlpool family (KitchenAid, Maytag) defrost drain access</h3>
    <p>Defrost drain on Whirlpool, KitchenAid, and Maytag freestanding units is accessible from the freezer rear panel, which we remove for the clear. Standard $200 to $300 drain clear. <a href="/brands/whirlpool-refrigerator-repair/">Whirlpool</a> · <a href="/brands/kitchenaid-refrigerator-repair/">KitchenAid</a> · <a href="/brands/maytag-refrigerator-repair/">Maytag</a>.</p>

    <h3 class="series-h3">GE Profile / Café / Monogram</h3>
    <p>Drain access similar to Whirlpool family. Haier-owned since 2016; recent units have improved defrost drain heater elements that reduce clog frequency. Older GE units (pre-2016) see drain clogs more often. <a href="/brands/ge-refrigerator-repair/">GE</a>.</p>

    <h3 class="series-h3">Bosch, Miele freestanding</h3>
    <p>European premium architecture, tighter integration. Defrost drain access more involved but same diagnostic logic. <a href="/brands/bosch-refrigerator-repair/">Bosch</a> · <a href="/brands/miele-refrigerator-repair/">Miele</a>.</p>
  </div>
</section>

<section class="section">
  <div class="container narrow">
    <p class="section-number">Diagnostic walkthrough</p>
    <h2 class="section-title">Practitioner sequence on every leak call.</h2>
    <ol class="num-list">
      <li><strong>Identify water location precisely.</strong> Inside-fridge, outside-front, outside-back, or under-the-unit. Different locations point to different causes.</li>
      <li><strong>Inspect inside-fridge floor and crisper area.</strong> Defrost drain clog signs: water pooling, sometimes ice formation at the drain inlet inside the freezer.</li>
      <li><strong>Pull unit out and inspect back.</strong> Inlet valve drip, supply line leak, drain pan condition.</li>
      <li><strong>Check ice maker fill tube for cracks.</strong> Visual inspection through freezer.</li>
      <li><strong>Coastal LA marine layer check.</strong> If puddle dries by noon and unit is in Santa Monica / Palisades / Malibu corridor, monitor for 24 hours before replacing parts.</li>
      <li><strong>Door seal inspection.</strong> Dollar-bill test on all sides of door; condensation pattern indicates seal compromise.</li>
    </ol>
  </div>
</section>

<section class="section section-gray">
  <div class="container narrow">
    <p class="section-number">Honest opinion</p>
    <h2 class="section-title">Sometimes the puddle on Monday morning is actually fog, not a malfunction.</h2>
    <p>Coastal LA homes (Santa Monica, Pacific Palisades, Malibu, parts of Marina del Rey) sit in the marine layer corridor. On dense-fog mornings, condensation forms on cold metal surfaces overnight; some homeowners see a small puddle at the base of the refrigerator and assume the unit is leaking. On follow-up the puddle dries by noon and doesn't return until the next foggy morning. That's not a leak. We diagnose and confirm before replacing any parts; if the pattern matches marine-layer condensation, the visit is $89 diagnostic only and we make a recommendation about humidity management or a small absorbent mat. Honest answer: don't pay for a repair you don't need.</p>
    <p>The other case where the visit is $89-only: defrost drain that's clearing fine but the customer found one isolated puddle from a single defrost cycle event (door left open during a meal prep, ice tray spilled). We confirm normal operation, no parts needed.</p>
  </div>
</section>

